{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"14ee90f1-76e3-4bdb-9db9-fac963bebe7b","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events mapper** in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Each platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `OnDestroy` on Android; `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate` on iOS).\n- The handlers receive the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), giving you full access if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9e4b525c-35fd-4009-9ba8-660d85772da1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I can answer directly.","outputTokens":363,"requestId":"F3E0:15198A:1EF2D23:22C0DA7:69E819FE"},"id":"ca7a44f7-991a-49ce-a50a-35074db86387","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:44:54.220Z","parentId":"7b428ec1-2e5f-4354-90d2-8d23b0ece9ab"}
